The '''Wake clan''' (和気氏) was a Japanese [[clan]] that bore the name "Wake" as their [[uji|family name]].

The clan was a powerful local family based in {{ill|Wake District, Okayama|ja|和気郡|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Bizen Province|ja|備前国|12=draft|12=draft}}, which was historically called "Fujino District." They claimed descent from {{ill|Nuteshiwake-no-mikoto|ja|鐸石別命|12=draft|12=draft}}, a son of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|ja|垂仁天皇|12=draft|12=draft}}. The name was also sometimes written as "Betsu clan" (別氏). Their noble titles ({{ill|Kabane|ja|姓|12=draft|12=draft}}) changed over time: they held the title [[Kimi (kabane)|Kimi]] (公), later becoming [[Mahito (kabane)|Mahito]] (真人), [[Sukune (kabane)|Sukune]] (宿禰), and finally, in [[774]] ({{ill|Hōki era|ja|宝亀|12=draft|12=draft}} 5), they were granted the title [[Asomi|Asomi]] (朝臣).

== Overview ==
During the [[Nara period]], {{ill|Wake no Hiromushi|ja|和気広虫|12=draft|12=draft}} (who later became a Buddhist nun and took the name Hōkinni) and her younger brother {{ill|Wake no Kiyomaro|ja|和気清麻呂|12=draft|12=draft}} gained prominence due to their role in the {{ill|Usa Hachiman Shrine Oracle Incident|ja|宇佐八幡宮神託事件|12=draft|12=draft}}, which involved resisting the influence of the Buddhist monk {{ill|Dōkyō|ja|道鏡|12=draft|12=draft}}. As a result, they rose in Rank within the [[Imperial court]] and were granted the clan title of "Wake Asomi" (和気朝臣) from their previous title "Fujinowake Mahito" (藤野別真人).

Kiyomaro’s son, {{ill|Wake no Hiroyo|ja|和気広世|12=draft|12=draft}}, and other descendants became scholars and served the court. Hiroyo established the {{ill|Kōbun-in|ja|弘文院|12=draft|12=draft}}, a special educational institution for members of the Wake clan, considered one of the [[Daigaku betsu-sō|private academies for aristocratic families]]{{efn|However, scholar {{ill|Hisao Kuki|ja|久木幸男|12=draft|12=draft}} has argued that Kōbun-in functioned more as a {{ill|library|ja|図書館|12=draft|12=draft}} rather than an academy.{{sfn|Kuki|1990|p={{page needed|date=October 2018}}}}}}.

Kiyomaro's fifth son, {{ill|Wake no Masatsuna|ja|和気真綱|12=draft|12=draft}}, rose to the Rank of {{ill|Sangi (councilor)|ja|参議|12=draft|12=draft}}, but later generations of the Wake clan did not achieve high court Ranks. Instead, they remained among the {{ill|Jige-ke|ja|地下家|12=draft|12=draft}}, a class of non-aristocratic court families. Despite this, they retained the privilege of receiving [[clan Ranks]] (氏爵) during imperial successions and events like {{ill|Sokutan tōji|ja|朔旦冬至|12=draft|12=draft}}, a privilege that continued until the [[Sengoku period]].

One of the most prominent families descended from the Wake clan was the {{ill|Nakarai family|ja|半井家|12=draft|12=draft}}, a line of {{ill|Kuge|ja|公家|1=Kuge|12=draft|12=draft}} court physicians who served the imperial family from the Sengoku period into the [[Edo period]].{{sfn|Namba|1997|p=72}} During the Edo period, {{ill|Nakarai Mansuke|ja|半井萬助|12=draft|12=draft}} established "Nakarai Mansuke Shoten," which later evolved into the pharmaceutical company {{ill|nacalai tesque|ja|ナカライテスク|12=draft|12=draft}}. Some members of the Wake clan also became samurai, such as {{ill|Wake no Chikashige|ja|和気致輔|12=draft|12=draft}}, who served under {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼義|12=draft|12=draft}}, a leader of the {{ill|Seiwa Genji|ja|清和源氏|12=draft|12=draft}}.

