Kiyomaro’s son, {{ill|Wake no Hiroyo|ja|和気広世|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wake no Hiroyo|qq=}}, and other descendants became scholars and served the court. Hiroyo established the {{ill|Kōbun-in|ja|弘文院|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōbun-in|qq=}}, a special educational institution for members of the Wake clan, considered one of the [[Daigaku betsu-sō|private academies for aristocratic families]]{{efn|However, scholar {{ill|Hisao Kuki|ja|久木幸男|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hisao Kuki|qq=}} has argued that Kōbun-in functioned more as a {{ill|library|ja|図書館|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/library|qq=}} rather than an academy.{{sfn|Kuki|1990|p={{page needed|date=October 2018}}}}}}.

Kiyomaro's fifth son, {{ill|Wake no Masatsuna|ja|和気真綱|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wake no Masatsuna|qq=}}, rose to the Rank of {{ill|Sangi (councilor)|ja|参議|1=Sangi (Japan)|lt=Sangi|2=ja|3=参議|4=ru|5=Санги|6=fr|7=Sangi_(Japon)|8=ko|9=참의_(일본사)|10=es|11=Sangi|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sangi (councilor)|qq=}}, but later generations of the Wake clan did not achieve high court Ranks. Instead, they remained among the {{ill|Jige-ke|ja|地下家|1=Jigeke|2=ja|3=地下家|lt=Jigeke|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jige-ke|13=User:Immanuelle/Jigeke|qq=}}, a class of non-aristocratic court families. Despite this, they retained the privilege of receiving [[clan Ranks]] (氏爵) during imperial successions and events like {{ill|Sokutan tōji|ja|朔旦冬至|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sokutan tōji|qq=}}, a privilege that continued until the [[Sengoku period]].

One of the most prominent families descended from the Wake clan was the {{ill|Nakarai family|ja|半井家|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakarai family|qq=}}, a line of {{ill|Kuge|ja|公家|1=Kuge|qq=|1=Kuge|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuge|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuge|qq=}} court physicians who served the imperial family from the Sengoku period into the [[Edo period]].{{sfn|Namba|1997|p=72}} During the Edo period, {{ill|Nakarai Mansuke|ja|半井萬助|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakarai Mansuke|qq=}} established "Nakarai Mansuke Shoten," which later evolved into the pharmaceutical company {{ill|nacalai tesque|ja|ナカライテスク|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/nacalai tesque|qq=}}. Some members of the Wake clan also became samurai, such as {{ill|Wake no Chikashige|ja|和気致輔|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wake no Chikashige|qq=}}, who served under {{ill|Minamoto no Yoritomo|ja|源頼義|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Minamoto no Yoritomo|qq=}}, a leader of the {{ill|Seiwa Genji|ja|清和源氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Seiwa Genji|qq=}}.

