The '''Wake clan''' (和気氏) was a Japanese {{ill|Clan|en|Clan|WD=Q211503|lt=Clan|1=Clan}} that bore the name "Wake" as their {{ill|Uji|en|Uji|WD=Q326956|lt=family name|1=Uji}}.

The clan was a powerful local family based in {{ill|Wake District, Okayama|en|Wake District, Okayama|WD=Q1155355|lt=Wake District, Okayama|1=Wake District, Okayama}}, {{ill|Bizen Province|en|Bizen Province|WD=Q1053688|lt=Bizen Province|1=Bizen Province}}, which was historically called "Fujino District." They claimed descent from {{ill|Nuteshiwake-no-mikoto|ja|鐸石別命|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nuteshiwake-no-mikoto|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, a son of {{ill|Emperor Suinin|en|Emperor Suinin|WD=Q314850|lt=Emperor Suinin|1=Emperor Suinin}}. The name was also sometimes written as "Betsu clan" (別氏). Their noble titles ({{ill|Kabane|ja|姓|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kabane|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}) changed over time: they held the title [[Kimi (kabane)|Kimi]] (公), later becoming [[Mahito (kabane)|Mahito]] (真人), [[Sukune (kabane)|Sukune]] (宿禰), and finally, in {{ill|774|en|774|WD=Q30528|lt=774|1=774}} ({{ill|Hōki|en|Hōki|WD=Q18520676|lt=Hōki era|1=Hōki}} 5), they were granted the title [[Asomi|Asomi]] (朝臣).

== Overview ==
During the {{ill|Nara period|en|Nara period|WD=Q189178|lt=Nara period|1=Nara period}}, {{ill|Wake no Hiromushi|ja|和気広虫|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wake no Hiromushi|1=Wake no Hiromushi|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q10921594}} (who later became a Buddhist nun and took the name Hōkinni) and her younger brother {{ill|Wake no Kiyomaro|en|Wake no Kiyomaro|WD=Q7961005|lt=Wake no Kiyomaro|1=Wake no Kiyomaro}} gained prominence due to their role in the {{ill|Usa Hachiman Shrine Oracle Incident|ja|宇佐八幡宮神託事件|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Usa Hachiman Shrine Oracle Incident|1=Dōkyō Incident|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11449036}}, which involved resisting the influence of the Buddhist monk {{ill|Dōkyō|en|Dōkyō|WD=Q1272718|lt=Dōkyō|1=Dōkyō}}. As a result, they rose in Rank within the [[:en:Imperial court|Imperial court]] and were granted the clan title of "Wake Asomi" (和気朝臣) from their previous title "Fujinowake Mahito" (藤野別真人).

Kiyomaro’s son, {{ill|Wake no Hiroyo|ja|和気広世|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wake no Hiroyo|1=Wake no hiroyo|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11417723}}, and other descendants became scholars and served the court. Hiroyo established the {{ill|Kōbun-in|ja|弘文院|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōbun-in|1=Kōbun-in|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11487348}}, a special educational institution for members of the Wake clan, considered one of the [[Daigaku betsu-sō|private academies for aristocratic families]]{{efn|However, scholar {{ill|Hisao Kuki|ja|久木幸男|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hisao Kuki|1=Yukio Hisaki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11369404}} has argued that Kōbun-in functioned more as a {{ill|Library|en|Library|WD=Q7075|lt=library|1=Library}} rather than an academy.{{sfn|Kuki|1990|p={{page needed|date=October 2018}}}}}}.

Kiyomaro's fifth son, {{ill|Wake no Masatsuna|ja|和気真綱|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wake no Masatsuna|1=Wake no Matsuna|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11417735}}, rose to the Rank of {{ill|Sangi (Japan)|en|Sangi (Japan)|WD=Q1133663|lt=Sangi|1=Sangi (Japan)}}, but later generations of the Wake clan did not achieve high court Ranks. Instead, they remained among the {{ill|Jige-ke|ja|地下家|1=Jigeke|2=ja|3=地下家|lt=Jigeke|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jige-ke|13=User:Immanuelle/Jigeke|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11424052}}, a class of non-aristocratic court families. Despite this, they retained the privilege of receiving [[clan Ranks]] (氏爵) during imperial successions and events like {{ill|Sokutan tōji|ja|朔旦冬至|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sokutan tōji|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 冬至|1=Winter solstice|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q207932}}, a privilege that continued until the {{ill|Sengoku period|en|Sengoku period|WD=Q204023|lt=Sengoku period|1=Sengoku period}}.

One of the most prominent families descended from the Wake clan was the {{ill|Nakarai family|ja|半井家|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakarai family|1=Nakarai family|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q121295088}}, a line of {{ill|Kuge|en|Kuge|WD=Q1196276|lt=Kuge|1=Kuge}} court physicians who served the imperial family from the Sengoku period into the {{ill|Edo period|en|Edo period|WD=Q184963|lt=Edo period|1=Edo period}}.{{sfn|Namba|1997|p=72}} During the Edo period, {{ill|Nakarai Mansuke|ja|半井萬助|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nakarai Mansuke|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}} established "Nakarai Mansuke Shoten," which later evolved into the pharmaceutical company {{ill|nacalai tesque|ja|ナカライテスク|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/nacalai tesque|1=Nacalai Tesque|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11323705}}. Some members of the Wake clan also became samurai, such as {{ill|Wake no Chikashige|ja|和気致輔|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Wake no Chikashige|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}, who served under {{ill|Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|en|Minamoto no Yoriyoshi|WD=Q3082851|lt=Minamoto no Yoritomo|1=Minamoto no Yoriyoshi}}, a leader of the {{ill|Seiwa Genji|en|Seiwa Genji|WD=Q2164991|lt=Seiwa Genji|1=Seiwa Genji}}.

